Pointers, Reference & Memory Management

Write a function that finds the largest of three fractions using pass-by-reference and return-by-reference.



1.	Key Concepts 

(a)	Pointer

A variable that stores the memory address of another variable.


Int x = 10;
Int *p = &x;

(b)	Reference

An alias (another name) for an existing variable.


Int x = 10;
Int &ref = x;

(c)	Pass-by-Reference

Function receives references → changes affect original variables.


(d)	Return-by-Reference

Function returns a reference to an existing variable (⚠ must not return local variables).




2.	Fraction Representation

We represent a fraction using numerator / denominator.

Struct Fraction {
    Int num;
    Int den;
};



3.	Comparing Fractions

To compare two fractions:

a/b > c/d \Rightarrow a \times d > c \times b



4.	Pseudocode (Exam Friendly)

BEGIN
  Define structure Fraction (numerator, denominator)

  FUNCTION largestFraction(ref f1, ref f2, ref f3) RETURNS ref
     SET largest = f1
     IF f2 > largest THEN
        Largest = f2
     END IF
     IF f3 > largest THEN
        Largest = f3
     END IF
     RETURN largest
  END FUNCTION
END



5.	C++ Program (Pass-by-Reference + Return-by-Reference)

#include <iostream>
Using namespace std;

Struct Fraction {
    Int num;
    Int den;
};

// Function returns a reference
Fraction& largestFraction(Fraction &f1, Fraction &f2, Fraction &f3) {
    Fraction *largest = &f1;

    If (f2.num * largest->den > largest->num * f2.den) {
        Largest = &f2;
    }

    If (f3.num * largest->den > largest->num * f3.den) {
        Largest = &f3;
    }

    Return *largest;
}

Int main() {
    Fraction f1 = {1, 2};
    Fraction f2 = {3, 4};
    Fraction f3 = {2, 3};

    Fraction &largest = largestFraction(f1, f2, f3);

    Cout << “Largest fraction is: “
         << largest.num << “/” << largest.den << endl;

    Return 0;
}

